Bombarder in the name of morality?
NEW YORK – Eloquence has always been one of the president's main assets.
It seems today, however, that his words have trapped him in a dilemma.
After stating last March that the United States "would not tolerate the use of chemical weapons against the Syrian people" and mentioning last year a "red line" that should not be crossed, Obama would lose face if he did not respond forcefully to the murder of over 1,000 civilians, attributed to the Syrian regime, using sarin gas.
Of course, the risk of losing face is not a valid reason to attack another country.
But why did Obama get himself involved in such rhetoric in the first place?
Why this particular line?
The U.S. Secretary of State John Kerry is right to describe the use of gas as "a moral obscenity."
But torturing children, the precursors of the civil war two years ago, is just as much so.
And is killing civilians with chemical substances morally more obscene than bombing them, shooting at them, or starving them to death?
It is commonly accepted, since the use of mustard gas during World War I, that some weapons are more immoral than others.
Massive destructive weapons, especially the nuclear bomb, certainly cause more damage and do so more quickly than conventional weapons.
But is there really a clear moral distinction between killing approximately 100,000 people with a single atomic bomb at Hiroshima and killing even more in a single night in Tokyo using incendiary bombs?
Was it more immoral to gas the Jews than to shoot them in mass graves?
A viewpoint, notably defended by Nicholas Kristof of the New York Times, argues that a swift punitive action could convince President Bashar al-Assad of Syria to abandon the use of chemical weapons and return to "more ordinary means of killing his people."
In my opinion, that makes no sense.
The question is surely about the massacre, not the methods used.
In all cases, moral outrage, however justified it may be, is not a sufficient reason to go to war.
Mao Zedong was responsible for the deaths of more than 40 million Chinese people in the 1950s and 1960s.
No sane person has suggested that a military intervention in China was a good idea.
In the 1980s, Saddam Hussein gassed hundreds of thousands of Iranians and Kurds—with the support of the United States.
Is it therefore a legal question? The use of chemical weapons constitutes a violation of international conventions, including the Chemical Weapons Convention, which Syria has never signed, and the Geneva Protocol, of which it is a party.
There are therefore valid reasons to consider Assad a war criminal, in which case he should be indicted by the International Criminal Court (ICC), established, by the way, by a treaty that the United States has never ratified.
But bypassing the United Nations and launching an illegal war to punish an illegal act is not a policy easily defendable.
One could argue, however, that the "international community," or Western countries, or the United States as the main Western power, must surely draw a line somewhere.
How can responsible governments simply turn away when innocent people are mass murdered?
Tolerating genocide is not acceptable.
But exactly where should one draw the line?
How many murders constitute genocide?
Thousands?
Hundreds of thousands?
Millions?
Does the number even matter?
Genocide is after all a matter of intent, there is a will to kill or persecute individuals because of their race, ethnic affiliation, or belief.
In principle, killing ten people for these reasons – or even two – would constitute a form of genocide.
The problem can be approached from another angle.
The question to reflect on before intervening militarily in a country is whether this action has a chance of improving the situation, saving lives, and making the world a safer place.
Yes, violence against civilians, whether through sarin gas or combat helicopters, is a moral obscenity.
Answering it requires asking: what is the best solution?
Justice and morality have little to do with such a decision.
Like the actions of the ICC, "humanitarian intervention" is more likely to produce results in a weak country (for example, Serbia, Mali, or Sierra Leone) than in the case of a major power.
No one would consider launching missile strikes on China or Russia in the name of defending human rights or enforcing international norms and conventions related to war.
Syria, as many have pointed out, is not Libya or Mali.
It is not also a major power.
But the civil war raging there has already spilled over its borders, involving more important countries, including Iran, Turkey, and Russia.
There is no doubt that a regional conflagration would be infinitely worse than the moral obscenities of a civil war.
It is by no means certain that an American intervention would reduce the risk of a broader conflict.
In fact, some supporters of a U.S. intervention—both neoconservatives and "liberal hawks"—seem to desire the opposite: they call for a war with Iran.
And Obama likely established a link in his mind between the red line regarding Syria and the one he drew for Iran, perhaps just as thoughtlessly, to prevent it from developing nuclear weapons.
What, then, should we expect from American strikes on Syrian targets, when Obama has already indicated that they were not intended to overthrow the Syrian regime?
They will not end the civil war.
But a single missile would make the United States a direct participant in this war, triggering a resurgence of violence.
Taking this risk to save Obama's honor does not seem particularly prudent.
This view is shared by many Syrians, including among the rebels.
It is the opinion of most Europeans.
And a majority of Americans.
It may even be Obama's own view, which is why he is desperately trying to buy time by delegating to the U.S. Congress the authority to use military force in Syria.
Since taking office, his relations with Congress have far from been easy.
But he now needs it more than ever to cover his back.
